  "text": "[ Skip to main content ](https://discuss.python.org/t/asyncio-best-practices/12576#main-container)\n[ ![Discussions on Python.org](https://us1.discourse-cdn.com/flex002/uploads/python1/original/1X/c7591c98caf3b31d4d9c6f322f41ed9d80a50800.png) ](https://discuss.python.org/)\nSign Up Log In\n  *   * ​ \n  * ​ \n\n\n​ \nPlease read our [Community Guidelines](https://discuss.python.org/guidelines/) that are tailored to this space in addition to the Python Software Foundation Code of Conduct that we’re bound by.\nReach out to [@moderators](https://discuss.python.org/groups/moderators) with any questions.\n#  [ Asyncio best practices ](https://discuss.python.org/t/asyncio-best-practices/12576)\n[Async-SIG](https://discuss.python.org/c/async-sig/20)\nYou have selected **0** posts.\n[ select all ](https://discuss.python.org/t/asyncio-best-practices/12576)\n[ cancel selecting ](https://discuss.python.org/t/asyncio-best-practices/12576)\n[ Dec 2021  ](https://discuss.python.org/t/asyncio-best-practices/12576/1 \"Jump to the first post\")\n1 / 1 \nDec 2021 \n[ Dec 2021 ](https://discuss.python.org/t/asyncio-best-practices/12576/1)\n##  post by TobiasHT on Dec 16, 2021 \n[ ![](https://sea2.discourse-cdn.com/flex002/user_avatar/discuss.python.org/tobiasht/48/23304_2.png) ](https://discuss.python.org/u/tobiasht)\n[ TobiasHT  ](https://discuss.python.org/u/tobiasht)\n[ Dec 2021 ](https://discuss.python.org/t/asyncio-best-practices/12576 \"Post date\")\nSo I thought it’d be great to catalog some of the best practices and patterns to follow while writing asynchronous code in Python, in order to help guide all developers who are planning to use this awesome feature on how to use it right.  \nWhat I mention here is not ultimate and might need to be corrected by Devs who have used this feature longer that I have, and also updated with more design patterns.\n###  [](https://discuss.python.org/t/asyncio-best-practices/12576#p-43808-h-1asyncawait-usage-1)1)async/await usage\nAsync functions are not necessarily asynchronous. I’ve noticed that coroutines shall run in order as they have been written in code, which isn’t exactly asynchronous but generally synchronous in nature. For example\n\n```\n\n\n\n\nimport asyncio\nimport time\nasync def waiter (secs):\n    time.sleep(secs)\n\nasync def main():\n    await waiter(1)\n    await waiter(2)\n    await waiter(3)\n\nasyncio.run(main())\n\n```\n\nSuch a program will run from top to bottom just as a synchronous program would. So in order to make it asynchronous, you have to interact with the asyncio library\n###  [](https://discuss.python.org/t/asyncio-best-practices/12576#p-43808-h-2-do-not-create-functions-with-long-running-loops-2)2) Do not create functions with long running loops\nHaving function that contain long running loops cause the event loop to halt until the function finishes, which causes lag.  \nThe best way to go around this is to rely on the already existing event loop and just schedule every iteration of your function loop onto the event loop. For example\n\n```\n\n\n\n\ndef long_runner(value):\n    loop = asyncio.get_running_loop()\n    if (value <= 1_000):\n        loop.call_soon(long_runner((value+1)))\n\n```\n\n###  [](https://discuss.python.org/t/asyncio-best-practices/12576#p-43808-h-3-using-tasks-3)3) using tasks\nI think using tasks is the equivalent of manually scheduling functions on the event loop since in this case, the tasks shall be tracked by the event loop.  \nI don’t think I can explain this concept better than [@ambv](https://discuss.python.org/u/ambv) on the series he created about asyncio,\n![](https://us1.discourse-cdn.com/flex002/uploads/python1/original/2X/a/aace902f8de78eca574102cd88a540abc5519a25.jpeg)\n[ import asyncio: Learn Python's AsyncIO #3 - Using Coroutines ](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-CzqsgaXUM8&t=66s \"import asyncio: Learn Python's AsyncIO #3 - Using Coroutines\")\nThere exists more patterns that we can use and share in order to build really great applications with asyncio, so I’m hoping this topics could act as a catalogue to these patterns and continously kept up-to-date with more current patterns\n  \n\n​ \n​ \n7.0k views  1 link \nReply\n  \n\n###  New & Unread Topics   \nTopic list, column headers with buttons are sortable.  \n|  Topic   |  Replies   |  Views   |  Activity   |  \n| --- | --- | --- | --- |  \n|  [Asyncio: How to merge two streams](https://discuss.python.org/t/asyncio-how-to-merge-two-streams/106616) [Async-SIG](https://discuss.python.org/c/async-sig/20)  |  [ 52 ](https://discuss.python.org/t/asyncio-how-to-merge-two-streams/106616/1)  |  837  |  [Apr 10](https://discuss.python.org/t/asyncio-how-to-merge-two-streams/106616/53)  |  \n|  [Getting socket options in asyncio server](https://discuss.python.org/t/getting-socket-options-in-asyncio-server/106863) [Async-SIG](https://discuss.python.org/c/async-sig/20)  |  [ 2 ](https://discuss.python.org/t/getting-socket-options-in-asyncio-server/106863/1)  |  122  |  [Apr 6](https://discuss.python.org/t/getting-socket-options-in-asyncio-server/106863/3)  |  \n|  [Testing asyncio.tools.get_all_awaited_by()](https://discuss.python.org/t/testing-asyncio-tools-get-all-awaited-by/92805) [Async-SIG](https://discuss.python.org/c/async-sig/20)  |  [ 2 ](https://discuss.python.org/t/testing-asyncio-tools-get-all-awaited-by/92805/1)  |  207  |  [May 2025](https://discuss.python.org/t/testing-asyncio-tools-get-all-awaited-by/92805/3)  |  \n|  [Does AsyncExitStack keep long-running code alive?](https://discuss.python.org/t/does-asyncexitstack-keep-long-running-code-alive/104656) [Async-SIG](https://discuss.python.org/c/async-sig/20)  |  [ 1 ](https://discuss.python.org/t/does-asyncexitstack-keep-long-running-code-alive/104656/1)  |  210  |  [Oct 2025](https://discuss.python.org/t/does-asyncexitstack-keep-long-running-code-alive/104656/2)  |  \n|  [New research project: Cancel scopes and level cancellation on asyncio](https://discuss.python.org/t/new-research-project-cancel-scopes-and-level-cancellation-on-asyncio/107031) [Async-SIG](https://discuss.python.org/c/async-sig/20)  |  [ 5 ](https://discuss.python.org/t/new-research-project-cancel-scopes-and-level-cancellation-on-asyncio/107031/1)  |  311  |  [28d](https://discuss.python.org/t/new-research-project-cancel-scopes-and-level-cancellation-on-asyncio/107031/6)  |  \n###  Want to read more? Browse other topics in [Async-SIG](https://discuss.python.org/c/async-sig/20) or [view latest topics](https://discuss.python.org/latest). \nInvalid date \n"
